Below is a **complete, self‑contained design** for the OCaml side of the binding and the C/C++ glue that makes the hot‑path “call a user supplied OCaml function for every block” as cheap as possible while keeping the OCaml API tidy and safe.

*The design assumes you have the BlockSci C++ library available (the header `blocksci/chain.hpp` is the public entry point).  
The C stub is compiled as a C++ source file (`.cpp`) because it needs to talk to the C++ API, but it is written with the OCaml C‑API only.*

---

## 1.  The OCaml public interface – `Blocksci.mli`

```ocaml
(*--------------------------------------------------------------------
   Blocksci – OCaml bindings for the BlockSci blockchain‑analysis engine
   --------------------------------------------------------------------*)

(** Opaque handle to a BlockSci chain (a collection of blocks). *)
type chain

(** Opaque handle to a single block.  The value is only valid for the
    duration of the callback passed to [iter] / [iter_until]; if you
    need to keep a block around, copy the fields you need. *)
type block

(** {1 Construction / destruction} *)

(** Open a BlockSci data directory.  Raises [Invalid_argument] if the
    path cannot be opened or does not contain a valid chain. *)
val open_chain : string -> chain

(** Close a chain and release all native resources.  After this call the
    [chain] value must not be used again.  It is safe (and a good idea) to
    call this even if an exception escaped from a previous iteration. *)
val close : chain -> unit

(** {1 Block fields – cheap getters} *)

val block_hash      : block -> string          (** 32‑byte hex string *)
val block_height    : block -> int
val block_timestamp : block -> int64          (** Unix epoch seconds *)
val block_tx_count  : block -> int
val block_size      : block -> int            (** bytes *)

(** {1 Iteration primitives} *)

(** Iterate over *all* blocks in the chain.  The supplied callback is
    invoked once for each block, in height order.  The callback runs in
    the OCaml runtime, so it may raise; if it does, iteration stops and
    the exception propagates to the caller.  The [block] value passed to
    the callback is a cheap wrapper – no allocation is performed for
    each iteration step. *)
val iter : chain -> (block -> unit) -> unit

(** Iterate until a predicate becomes true.  The predicate receives the
    current block and must return [true] to stop iteration (the block
    that caused the predicate to return true is *not* processed).  The
    predicate may raise; the exception propagates just like in [iter]. *)
val iter_until : chain -> (block -> bool) -> unit

(** {1 Low‑level helpers – for advanced users} *)

(** Access the raw native pointer (for C‑FFI users).  Do **NOT** use
    this value from OCaml code – it is only meant for the C stub. *)
val _native_chain_ptr : chain -> nativeint
```

### Design notes

* **Performance** – The hot loop lives in the C++ side.  For each block we only allocate **one** OCaml custom block (the wrapper) *once* at the start of the iteration and then **reuse** it for every step.  The wrapper simply updates its internal C++ pointer, so the per‑iteration overhead is a single pointer write plus a `caml_callback` call (the cheapest possible crossing).  

* **Safety** – The wrapper is documented as “valid only during the callback”.  This prevents the GC from holding stale pointers and makes it clear that the user must copy any data they need.

* **Exception handling** – If the OCaml callback raises, the C stub aborts the loop and re‑raises the exception, preserving the usual OCaml semantics.

* **Memory management** – The `chain` custom block owns a `BlockSci::Chain*` and is freed by a finaliser (also called by `close`).  The `block` wrapper does **not** own its native block; it is merely a view.

---

## 2.  The C/C++ stub – `blocksci_stubs.cpp`

> **Compile command (example)**
> ```sh
> ocamlopt -c blocksci_stubs.cpp -I $(ocamlc -where) \
>          -ccopt -std=c++17 -ccopt -O3 -ccopt -fPIC
> ocamlopt -a -o libblocksci.cmxa blocksci_stubs.o
> ```
> Link the final executable / library with `-lblocksci -lstdc++`.

```cpp
/*====================================================================
   blocksci_stubs.cpp  –  OCaml <-> BlockSci glue
   ====================================================================*/

#define CAML_NAME_SPACE
#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>

#include <blocksci/chain.hpp>   // public BlockSci header
#include <string>

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
   1.  OCaml custom blocks
   ----------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* ----- chain ---------------------------------------------------- */
struct caml_chain {
    BlockSci::Chain *ptr;          // owned – freed in finaliser
};

static void caml_chain_finalize(value v)
{
    caml_chain *c = (caml_chain *)Data_custom_val(v);
    if (c->ptr) {
        delete c->ptr;
        c->ptr = nullptr;
    }
}

static struct custom_operations caml_chain_ops = {
    "Blocksci.chain",
    caml_chain_finalize,
    custom_compare_default,
    custom_hash_default,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_compare_ext_default,
    custom_fixed_length_default
};

/* ----- block (wrapper, not owned) ------------------------------- */
struct caml_block {
    const BlockSci::Block *ptr;    // NOT owned – just a view
};

static void caml_block_finalize(value) { /* no-op */ }

static struct custom_operations caml_block_ops = {
    "Blocksci.block",
    caml_block_finalize,
    custom_compare_default,
    custom_hash_default,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_compare_ext_default,
    custom_fixed_length_default
};

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
   2.  Helper: allocate a fresh OCaml wrapper for a block pointer.
   ----------------------------------------------------------------- */
static value caml_wrap_block(const BlockSci::Block *blk)
{
    CAMLparam0();
    CAMLlocal1(v);
    v = caml_alloc_custom(&caml_block_ops, sizeof(caml_block), 0, 1);
    caml_block *b = (caml_block *)Data_custom_val(v);
    b->ptr = blk;
    CAMLreturn(v);
}

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
   3.  Exposed primitives
   ----------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* ----- open_chain ------------------------------------------------ */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_open_chain(value v_path)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_path);
    CAMLlocal1(v_chain);
    const char *path = String_val(v_path);

    // Construct the native Chain object – may throw std::exception
    BlockSci::Chain *chain = nullptr;
    try {
        chain = new BlockSci::Chain(path);
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_failwith(e.what());
    }

    v_chain = caml_alloc_custom(&caml_chain_ops, sizeof(caml_chain), 0, 1);
    caml_chain *c = (caml_chain *)Data_custom_val(v_chain);
    c->ptr = chain;

    CAMLreturn(v_chain);
}

/* ----- close ----------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_close(value v_chain)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_chain);
    caml_chain *c = (caml_chain *)Data_custom_val(v_chain);
    if (c->ptr) {
        delete c->ptr;
        c->ptr = nullptr;
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ----- _native_chain_ptr (debug helper) -------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_native_chain_ptr(value v_chain)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_chain);
    caml_chain *c = (caml_chain *)Data_custom_val(v_chain);
    CAMLreturn(caml_copy_nativeint((nativeint)(c->ptr)));
}

/* ----- block getters (hash, height, …) --------------------------- */
static inline const BlockSci::Block* unwrap_block(value v_blk)
{
    caml_block *b = (caml_block *)Data_custom_val(v_blk);
    return b->ptr;
}

/* block_hash : block -> string */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_block_hash(value v_blk)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_blk);
    const BlockSci::Block *blk = unwrap_block(v_blk);
    std::string h = blk->hash().toHex();          // assume BlockSci API
    CAMLreturn(caml_copy_string(h.c_str()));
}

/* block_height : block -> int */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_block_height(value v_blk)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_blk);
    const BlockSci::Block *blk = unwrap_block(v_blk);
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(blk->height()));
}

/* block_timestamp : block -> int64 */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_block_timestamp(value v_blk)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_blk);
    const BlockSci::Block *blk = unwrap_block(v_blk);
    CAMLreturn(caml_copy_int64(blk->timestamp()));
}

/* block_tx_count : block -> int */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_block_tx_count(value v_blk)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_blk);
    const BlockSci::Block *blk = unwrap_block(v_blk);
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(blk->txCount()));
}

/* block_size : block -> int */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_block_size(value v_blk)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_blk);
    const BlockSci::Block *blk = unwrap_block(v_blk);
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(blk->size()));
}

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
   4.  The hot iteration loops
   ----------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* Helper that creates a *single* reusable OCaml wrapper and then
   repeatedly updates its internal pointer before calling the OCaml
   callback.  This is the key to keep the per‑iteration cost low. */
static void iterate_blocks(BlockSci::Chain *chain,
                           value ocaml_cb,
                           bool stop_on_true,
                           value ocaml_pred /* only used when stop_on_true */)
{
    CAMLparam3(ocaml_cb, ocaml_pred, Val_unit);
    /* Allocate the reusable wrapper once */
    value v_block = caml_wrap_block(nullptr);  // ptr will be overwritten
    caml_block *b = (caml_block *)Data_custom_val(v_block);

    try {
        for (auto it = chain->blocks().begin(); it != chain->blocks().end(); ++it) {
            b->ptr = &*it;               // update view

            if (stop_on_true) {
                /* predicate : block -> bool */
                int should_stop = Bool_val(caml_callback(ocaml_pred, v_block));
                if (should_stop) break;
            } else {
                caml_callback(ocaml_cb, v_block);
            }
        }
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_failwith(e.what());
    } catch (...) {
        caml_failwith("unknown C++ exception in BlockSci iterator");
    }
    CAMLreturn0;
}

/* iter : chain -> (block -> unit) -> unit */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_iter(value v_chain, value v_cb)
{
    CAMLparam2(v_chain, v_cb);
    caml_chain *c = (caml_chain *)Data_custom_val(v_chain);
    if (!c->ptr) caml_failwith("Blocksci.iter: chain already closed");
    iterate_blocks(c->ptr, v_cb, false, Val_unit);
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* iter_until : chain -> (block -> bool) -> unit */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_iter_until(value v_chain, value v_pred)
{
    CAMLparam2(v_chain, v_pred);
    caml_chain *c = (caml_chain *)Data_custom_val(v_chain);
    if (!c->ptr) caml_failwith("Blocksci.iter_until: chain already closed");
    iterate_blocks(c->ptr, Val_unit, true, v_pred);
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
   5.  Register the primitives (optional, for ocamlc -custom)
   ----------------------------------------------------------------- */

static struct ocaml_named_value {
    const char *name;
    value (*fn)(value);
} primitives[] = {
    {"Blocksci.open_chain",            caml_blocksci_open_chain},
    {"Blocksci.close",                 caml_blocksci_close},
    {"Blocksci._native_chain_ptr",     caml_blocksci_native_chain_ptr},
    {"Blocksci.block_hash",            caml_blocksci_block_hash},
    {"Blocksci.block_height",          caml_blocksci_block_height},
    {"Blocksci.block_timestamp",       caml_blocksci_block_timestamp},
    {"Blocksci.block_tx_count",        caml_blocksci_block_tx_count},
    {"Blocksci.block_size",            caml_blocksci_block_size},
    {"Blocksci.iter",                  caml_blocksci_iter},
    {"Blocksci.iter_until",            caml_blocksci_iter_until},
    {nullptr, nullptr}
};

extern "C" void caml_register_named_values(void)
{
    for (struct ocaml_named_value *p = primitives; p->name != nullptr; ++p)
        caml_register_named_value(p->name, p->fn);
}
```

### How the pieces fit together

| OCaml name                     | C stub implementation                         |
|--------------------------------|----------------------------------------------|
| `open_chain`                   | `caml_blocksci_open_chain`                    |
| `close`                        | `caml_blocksci_close`                         |
| `_native_chain_ptr`            | `caml_blocksci_native_chain_ptr`              |
| `block_hash`, `block_height` …| individual getters (`caml_blocksci_block_*`) |
| `iter`                         | `caml_blocksci_iter` → `iterate_blocks`       |
| `iter_until`                   | `caml_blocksci_iter_until` → `iterate_blocks` |

The **hot loop** lives in `iterate_blocks`.  The only allocations performed are:

* the **custom block wrapper** (`v_block`) – created *once* before the loop.
* the **callback closure** – supplied by the user, allocated outside the loop.

Every iteration does:

1. Write a new pointer into the wrapper (`b->ptr = …`).
2. Call the OCaml closure (`caml_callback`).

Both steps are O(1) and have a tiny constant factor.  Because the wrapper is reused, we avoid the per‑iteration `caml_alloc_custom` that would otherwise dominate the cost when looping over 800 M blocks.

### Exception flow

* If the native BlockSci iterator throws (e.g. I/O error), we translate it into an OCaml `Failure` via `caml_failwith`.
* If the OCaml callback raises, `caml_callback` propagates the exception back to the C code; the `try … catch` block is *not* entered, and the exception bubbles out of `iterate_blocks` to the OCaml caller, exactly as if the user had called any OCaml function.

### Memory safety

* The `chain` custom block owns its native `BlockSci::Chain*` and is freed by the finaliser *or* by an explicit `close`.  The finaliser is added automatically by OCaml’s GC, so forgetting to call `close` is still safe (just less deterministic).
* The `block` wrapper does **not** own the underlying `BlockSci::Block`.  The wrapper is only valid while the iterator is active; documentation makes this explicit.  If a user needs a persistent representation they should copy the fields they care about (e.g. using the getters above).

### Building & linking

```sh
# Compile the C++ stub (needs a C++ compiler)
ocamlopt -c -I $(ocamlc -where) \
         -ccopt -std=c++17 -ccopt -O3 \
         blocksci_stubs.cpp

# Build a library (optional)
ocamlopt -a -o libblocksci.cmxa blocksci_stubs.o

# Example program linking it:
ocamlopt -I . -c my_app.ml
ocamlopt -o my_app unix.cmxa libblocksci.cmxa my_app.o -lblocksci -lstdc++
```

---

## 3.  Example OCaml usage

```ocaml
(* my_app.ml ----------------------------------------------------------- *)
let () =
  let chain = Blocksci.open_chain "/data/blocksci/bitcoin" in
  try
    (* Very cheap per‑block work – just count blocks with > 1000 txs *)
    let cnt = ref 0 in
    Blocksci.iter chain (fun blk ->
        if Blocksci.block_tx_count blk > 1000 then incr cnt);
    Printf.printf "Blocks with >1000 txs: %d\n%!" !cnt;

    (* Stop early once we see a block older than 2010‑01‑01 *)
    let cutoff = Int64.of_int 1262304000 in   (* 2010‑01‑01 00:00:00 UTC *)
    Blocksci.iter_until chain (fun blk ->
        Blocksci.block_timestamp blk < cutoff);
    Printf.printf "Stopped at the first block before 2010.\n%!"
  with
  | Failure msg -> prerr_endline ("BlockSci error: " ^ msg)
  | exn -> prerr_endline ("Unexpected exception: " ^ Printexc.to_string exn);
  Blocksci.close chain
```

Running this program walks the whole chain (≈ 800 M blocks) with a per‑block cost that is essentially just a pointer write and a single OCaml callback, which is as close as you can get to native speed while still giving the user the full flexibility of OCaml.

---

### TL;DR

* **`.mli`** – clean, high‑level OCaml API (`chain`, `block`, getters, `iter`, `iter_until`).
* **`blocksci_stubs.cpp`** – custom blocks for `chain` and `block`, a *single* reusable wrapper for the hot loop, exception‑safe crossing between C++ and OCaml, and all the glue needed to expose the API.
* The design follows the pattern used by data‑frame libraries (Polars, pandas): the user supplies a closure that is called for every row/block; the C++ side does the heavy lifting, while the OCaml side sees only a tiny, well‑documented wrapper.
